Create a JavaScript program that allows users to draw on an HTML5 canvas
model
```javascript
const canvas = document.getElementById('canvas');
const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

let isDrawing = false;
let x = 0;
let y = 0;

canvas.addEventListener('mousedown', (e) => {
  isDrawing = true;
  x = e.clientX;
  y = e.clientY;
});

canvas.addEventListener('mousemove', (e) => {
  if (isDrawing) {
    let dx = e.clientX - x;
    let dy = e.clientY - y;
    x = e.clientX;
    y = e.clientY;

    ctx.beginPath();
    ctx.moveTo(x - dx, y - dy);
    ctx.lineTo(x, y);
    ctx.stroke();
  }
});

canvas.addEventListener('mouseup', () => {
  isDrawing = false;
});
```

**HTML:**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
  </head>

  <body>
    <canvas id="canvas"></canvas>
  </body>
</html>
```

**Explanation:**

* The program creates a variable `isDrawing` to track whether the user is currently drawing.
* The program stores the initial mouse position `x` and `y` when the user clicks the mouse button.
* When the user moves the mouse, the program checks if `isDrawing` is `true`. If it is, it draws a line from the previous mouse position to the current position.
* When the user releases the mouse button, `isDrawing` is set to `false`, preventing further drawing.

**Additional Notes:**

* You can customize the line color and thickness by changing the `ctx.strokeStyle` and `ctx.lineWidth` properties.
* You can add other drawing functions, such as circles, squares, and triangles, by modifying the `ctx.beginPath()` and `ctx.stroke()` methods.
* To enable drawing on a specific area of the canvas, you can use a `clip` function to restrict the drawing area.

